## Summary

### What was built

**`src/monopoly/simulate.py`** — Added `simulate_landing_frequencies(n_rolls, seed)`:
- Single-player one-roll-per-step simulation that faithfully implements the same model as `markov.build_transition_matrix()`
- Jail: ROLL_DOUBLES strategy with 3-turn cycle + forced release (matching Markov's jail states 40/41/42)
- Cards: exact same Chance (6/16 non-move, 10/16 movement) and Community Chest (14/16 non-move) fractions
- Triple-doubles: applies the same uniform 1/36 correction per doubles roll (not explicit consecutive tracking, to match the 43-state Markov chain's approximation)
- Go To Jail (pos 30) always redirects to jail; position 30 always has frequency 0

**`tests/test_cross_validation.py`** — 10 tests total:
- 9 fast unit tests (shape, sum-to-1, reproducibility, zero at pos 30, jail is most frequent, etc.)
- 1 slow cross-validation test (`@pytest.mark.slow`, 5M rolls, seed=42)

### Key finding
Explicit consecutive-doubles tracking creates a statistically different Markov chain (~0.2 pp jail discrepancy). The 43-state model uses a first-order approximation for triple-doubles; matching that approximation (1/36 uniform correction per doubles roll) gives <0.033 pp max deviation across all 40 squares.

### Results
- Max delta: **0.033 pp** (tolerance: ±0.1 pp) ✓  
- Chi-squared p-value: **0.844** (need > 0.01) ✓  
- All 830 tests pass (820 existing + 10 new) ✓
